<h2>HVAC Systems in Oregon</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Oregon's diverse climate zones require different HVAC approaches depending on location and elevation. Western Oregon's marine climate features mild winters with temperatures rarely falling below 30¬∞F and comfortable summers with highs typically in the 80s. This moderate climate makes heat pumps an excellent choice, providing both heating and cooling efficiently throughout the year. Eastern Oregon's more continental climate with colder winters and hotter summers may require supplemental heating systems or higher-capacity equipment.</p>

<p>The state's heating season typically runs from October through April, with cooling needs concentrated in July and August. Most Oregon homes prioritize heating efficiency over cooling capacity, making systems with high Heating Seasonal Performance Factor (HSPF) ratings more valuable than those optimized solely for cooling efficiency. However, as summer temperatures have increased in recent years, balanced systems providing both heating and cooling capabilities are becoming increasingly important.</p>

<p>Recommended SEER ratings for Oregon range from 14-16 for most applications, with higher ratings justified in areas experiencing longer cooling seasons. Heat pump systems are particularly well-suited to Oregon's climate, with ductless mini-split systems gaining popularity for their efficiency and zoned comfort control. Traditional forced-air systems remain common, but proper sizing and duct sealing are critical given Oregon's emphasis on building energy efficiency and the state's energy codes.</p>

